LXI. Sabine herb, called brathy by the Greeks, is of Nae-in. two kinds. One has a leaf like that of the tamarisk, the other like that of the cypress, for which reason some have called it the Cretan cypr-ess. Many use it instead of frankincense for fumigations 3 in medicines rnoreover a double dose is said to be equivalent in strength to a single dose of cinnamon. It reduces gatherings and checks corroding sores 3 an application cleanses ulcers, and used as a pessary or for fumigation it brings away the dead foetus. With honey it is used as an ointment for erysipelas and carbuncles; taken in wine it cures jaundice. By fumigation sabine herb is said to eure the pip in chickens.
